Featurization and Model Tuning Project¶

Data Description:¶

The actual concrete compressive strength (MPa) for a given mixture under a specific age (days) was determined from laboratory. Data is in raw form (not scaled). The data has 8 quantitative input variables, and 1 quantitative output variable, and 1030 instances (observations).

Domain:¶

Cement manufacturing

Context:¶

Concrete is the most important material in civil engineering. The concrete compressive strength is a highly nonlinear function of age and ingredients. These ingredients include cement, blast furnace slag, fly ash, water, superplasticizer, coarse aggregate, and fine aggregate.

Attribute Information:¶

Cement : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
Blast : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
Fly ash : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
Water : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
Superplasticizer : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
Coarse Aggregate : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
Fine Aggregate : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
Age : day (1~365)
Concrete compressive strength measured in MPa

Learning Outcomes:¶

Exploratory Data Analysis
Building ML models for regression
Hyper parameter tuning

Objective:¶

Modeling of strength of high performance concrete using Machine Learning

Steps and tasks:¶

def numerical_feature_analysis(feature):
    feature_min=df[feature].min()
    feature_max=df[feature].max()
    feature_q1=np.quantile(df[feature],0.25)
    feature_q3=np.quantile(df[feature],0.75)
    feature_IQR=(feature_q3-feature_q1)
    feature_lower_whisker=feature_q1-(feature_IQR*1.5)
    feature_upper_whisker=feature_q3+(feature_IQR*1.5)

    print("Feature: ",feature)
    if (feature_lower_whisker<=feature_min) and (feature_upper_whisker>=feature_max):
        print("No outliers.")
    else:
        if (feature_upper_whisker<feature_max):
            print("Outliers are present in maximum. ",feature," above ",round(feature_upper_whisker,2)," are outliers and total are ",df[df[feature]>feature_upper_whisker][feature].count())
        if (feature_lower_whisker>feature_min):
            print("Outliers are present in minimum. ",feature," below ",round(feature_lower_whisker,2)," are outliers and total are ",df[df[feature]<feature_lower_whisker][feature].count())
    
    print("----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------")

c. Pick one strategy to address the presence of outliers and missing values and perform necessary imputation (10 marks)¶

Outlier Treatment:¶

Already outliers are captured in Univariate analysis through IQR approach.
After carefully going through outliers, it looks that capping process is better in this case. The reason being strength values of upper/lower whisker are almost in same range as outliers for each predictors.

Note: Since here we are doing capping process, it can be done before splitting the data into train and test. The reason being, impact is very minimal if we do this activity befor or after the data split.

In [80]:
def outlier_handler(feature):
    feature_min=df[feature].min()
    feature_max=df[feature].max()
    feature_q1=np.quantile(df[feature],0.25)
    feature_q3=np.quantile(df[feature],0.75)
    feature_IQR=(feature_q3-feature_q1)
    feature_lower_whisker=feature_q1-(feature_IQR*1.5)
    feature_upper_whisker=feature_q3+(feature_IQR*1.5)
    print(feature)
    if (feature_lower_whisker<=feature_min) and (feature_upper_whisker>=feature_max):
        print("No outliers.")
    else:
        print("changing outliers' value using capping.")
        if (feature_upper_whisker<feature_max):
            # Capping is done to replace outliers.
            df.loc[df[feature]>feature_upper_whisker ,feature] =feature_upper_whisker
        if (feature_lower_whisker>feature_min):
            # Capping is done to replace outliers.
            df.loc[df[feature]<feature_lower_whisker,feature] =feature_lower_whisker

Conclusion:¶

Above clearly states that all features are not equally important for all groups. Hence a single linear model for the entire dataset wouldn't work.
Even there are problems with linear models seperately built for each group because of too much heteroscedasticity.

Heteroscedasticity can create problems for Polynomial regression as well and also considering the low volume of dataset its better not to go for Polynomial Regression. Because it can lead to curse of dimensionality.

In this case, its better if we rely on Tree based algorithms which can handle these kind of datasets as trees splits happen in ranges for continuous features.

# Creating a function for Adjusted R^2 score
def adj_rsquared(r2_score,no_of_coef,sample_size):
    return (1-((1-r2_score)*(sample_size-1)/(sample_size-no_of_coef-1)))

def regression_model(model,model_name=None,X_train= X_train,X_test= X_test):
    if model_name is None:
        model_name=model.__class__.__name__
    model=model.fit(X_train,y_train)
    k=len(X_train.columns)
    n=X_test.shape[0]
    y_test_pred=model.predict(X_test)
    test_r2_score=r2_score(y_test,y_test_pred)
    test_adj_r2_score=adj_rsquared(test_r2_score,k,n)
    test_mean_squared_error =mean_squared_error(y_test,y_test_pred)
    print("Test results for ",model_name,":")
    print("Mean square Error:",test_mean_squared_error)
    print("R2 score:",test_r2_score)
    print("Adjusted R2 score:",test_adj_r2_score)
    # model_results.append({model_name:[model,np.round(test_r2_score,2),np.round(adj_r2_score,2)]})
    val_r2_score_list=[]
    val_adj_r2_score_list=[]
    val_mean_squared_error_list=[]
    rkf=RepeatedKFold(n_splits=5,n_repeats=5,random_state=1)
    sc=StandardScaler()
    k=len(X.columns)
    # Here we can use cross_validate sklearn function which has n_jobs param and can do parallel processing
    for train_idx,val_idx in rkf.split(X,y):
        X_train_fold, X_val_fold=X.iloc[train_idx,:],X.iloc[val_idx,:]
        y_train_fold, y_val_fold=y.iloc[train_idx],y.iloc[val_idx]
        # Scaling based on current train and validation dataset
        sc=sc.fit(X_train_fold)
        X_train_fold=pd.DataFrame(data=sc.transform(X_train_fold),columns=X_train_fold.columns)
        X_val_fold=pd.DataFrame(data=sc.transform(X_val_fold),columns=X_val_fold.columns)
        model=model.fit(X_train_fold,y_train_fold)
        y_val_fold_pred=model.predict(X_val_fold)
        val_r2_score=r2_score(y_val_fold,y_val_fold_pred)
        val_r2_score_list.append(val_r2_score)
        n=X_val_fold.shape[0]
        val_adj_r2_score_list.append(adj_rsquared(val_r2_score,k,n))
        val_mean_squared_error =mean_squared_error(y_val_fold,y_val_fold_pred)
        val_mean_squared_error_list.append(val_mean_squared_error)
        
    model_results.append({model_name:[model,
                                      np.round(test_r2_score,2),
                                      np.round(test_adj_r2_score,2),
                                      np.round(test_mean_squared_error,2),
                                      np.round(min(val_r2_score_list),2),
                                      np.round(np.percentile(val_r2_score_list,5),2),
                                      np.round(np.percentile(val_r2_score_list,25),2),
                                      np.round(np.percentile(val_r2_score_list,50),2),
                                      np.round(np.percentile(val_r2_score_list,75),2),
                                      np.round(np.percentile(val_r2_score_list,95),2),
                                      np.round(max(val_r2_score_list),2),
                                      np.round(np.mean(val_r2_score_list),2),
                                      np.round(np.std(val_r2_score_list),2),
                                      np.round(min(val_adj_r2_score_list),2),
                                      np.round(np.percentile(val_adj_r2_score_list,5),2),
                                      np.round(np.percentile(val_adj_r2_score_list,25),2),
                                      np.round(np.percentile(val_adj_r2_score_list,50),2),
                                      np.round(np.percentile(val_adj_r2_score_list,75),2),
                                      np.round(np.percentile(val_adj_r2_score_list,95),2),
                                      np.round(max(val_adj_r2_score_list),2),
                                      np.round(np.mean(val_adj_r2_score_list),2),
                                      np.round(np.std(val_adj_r2_score_list),2),
                                      np.round(min(val_mean_squared_error_list),2),
                                      np.round(np.percentile(val_mean_squared_error_list,5),2),
                                      np.round(np.percentile(val_mean_squared_error_list,25),2),
                                      np.round(np.percentile(val_mean_squared_error_list,50),2),
                                      np.round(np.percentile(val_mean_squared_error_list,75),2),
                                      np.round(np.percentile(val_mean_squared_error_list,95),2),
                                      np.round(max(val_mean_squared_error_list),2),
                                      np.round(np.mean(val_mean_squared_error_list),2),
                                      np.round(np.std(val_mean_squared_error_list),2)
                                     ]})
    return model

4. Deliverable -4 (Tuning the model) (20 marks)¶

a. Algorithms that you think will be suitable for this project (5 marks)¶

This we have already discussed during the cluster analysis part.

Inshort, definitely simple linear model is not sufficient because of how the data it is. All features are weak predictors(except cement) and they are very lowly correlated with Target(strength).
Also, on top of simple linear regression we can implement Polynomial feature processing to get the multiple combinations of predictors which can sometimes help in obtaining a better model.
If performance is bettered with Polynomial regression then we can implement Lasso to reduce the impact of curse of dimensionality.
Perhaps, Decission Trees can be a good choice in this scenario wherein it can split the data anywhere in range. But need to be careful with Tree algorithms on overfitting part.

b. Techniques employed to squeeze that extra performance out of the model without making it overfit or underfit (5 marks)¶

Conclusion:¶

By looking at above metrics, both XGBoost and Light GBM performed well.
However additionally Light GBM has performed well on Test dataset. And also Validation Adjusted R-square score and Coefficient of Variation of MSE is less for Light GBM when compared to XG Boost.
No. of trees required by Light GBM is less when compared to XG Boost.
Hence Light GBM with tuned hyper-parameter is the best model to predict the strength of Concrete.
